In mathematics, the Cartesian product of two sets A and B is denoted by A × B. It is the set of all ordered pairs (a, b) such that a ∈ A and b ∈ B. For example, if A = {1, 2} and B = {3, 4}, then A × B = {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}.

An ordered pair is a special type of set that contains two elements. The order of the elements in an ordered pair is important, so (1, 2) is not the same as (2, 1). A triple is an ordered set that contains three elements.

Cartesian products can be used to represent many different types of relationships. For example, the Cartesian product of the set of all people and the set of all jobs represents the set of all possible job assignments.

Ordered pairs and triples are often used in computer science to represent data structures such as lists and arrays.

Here are some examples of Cartesian products, ordered pairs, and triples:

* The Cartesian product of the set {1, 2} and the set {3, 4} is {(1, 3), (1, 4), (2, 3), (2, 4)}.
* The ordered pair (1, 2) has first element 1 and second element 2.
* The triple (1, 2, 3) has first element 1, second element 2, and third element 3.

